	 }    // end Stack Class       
```         In the above code, `List` and its subclasses (like 'Stack') have access to all methods of their superclass ('super class'). The delegation allows us not only adding elements but also getting them at a specific index.  This is an example where we use delegate pattern in Java by using interfaces for communication between classes which are part ways towards achieving loose coupling and high cohesion among different components within the system, as well maintaining encapsulation of data (like 'List' here).

